<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" box="[264,383,793,818]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[264,383,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" box="[312,748,833,859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Body long, slender, fragile (
<figureCitation box="[640,733,833,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" captionTargetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[368,1239,416,1814]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: lateral; B—carapace; C—rostrum, D— telson and left uropod, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Carapace (
<figureCitation box="[443,539,873,899]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" captionTargetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[368,1239,416,1814]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: lateral; B—carapace; C—rostrum, D— telson and left uropod, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) with short acute hepatic and supraorbital spines, hepatic and anterior ridges. Rostrum short (
<figureCitation box="[655,745,913,939]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" captionTargetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[368,1239,416,1814]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: lateral; B—carapace; C—rostrum, D— telson and left uropod, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) hardly elevated, apically acute, anterior margin vertically armed with single terminal tooth. No supra­orbital ridge, Cervical groove welldeveloped with small hepatic spine at its base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Strong suprabranchial ridge present. Eyes well developed, eyestalks lacking occular tubercle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" box="[312,764,1113,1139]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Telson distally rounded (
<figureCitation box="[603,750,1113,1139]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" captionTargetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[368,1239,416,1814]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: lateral; B—carapace; C—rostrum, D— telson and left uropod, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs.1A, 1D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Antennular peduncle (
<figureCitation box="[584,681,1153,1179]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" captionTargetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[368,1239,416,1814]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: lateral; B—carapace; C—rostrum, D— telson and left uropod, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs.1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[698,735,1153,1179]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[264,367,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[347,1279,321,1773]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[319,1296,302,1792]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sergestes brevispinatu, Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—clasping organ of lower antennular flgellum (left), ventral; 3 ap, I–VII, 1st to 7th segments; cp; B— left third maxilliped; C— left third maxilliped, dactylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051220/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">2A</figureCitation>
) about three­fourths as long as carapace, outer margin of segment 1 longer than that of segment 2. Armed with distolateral tooth on basal segment. Antennal flagellum more than twice length of body, divided into proximal and distal parts by short section of annuli forming double band. Inner flagellum in male clasping organ with deep proxmomesial notch whereas in female short, simple and straight spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Third maxilliped (
<figureCitation box="[530,684,1393,1419]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[264,367,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[347,1279,321,1773]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[319,1296,302,1792]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sergestes brevispinatu, Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—clasping organ of lower antennular flgellum (left), ventral; 3 ap, I–VII, 1st to 7th segments; cp; B— left third maxilliped; C— left third maxilliped, dactylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051220/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs. 2B, 2C</figureCitation>
) dactylii with single mesial spine on outer margin of subsegments 1 and 2. Outer distal spine on subsegment 1 seldom reaching beyond subsegment 2; outer distal spine on subsegment 2 seldom reaching beyond subsegment 4; outer distal spine on subsegment 4 very short; outer terminal spine on subsegment 6 usually less than length of inner terminal spine. Distal spines on outer margin of subsegments 1, 2 and 4 and outer terminal spine on subsegment 6 tending to be relatively shorter, and inner margin spines more numerous in females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" box="[312,1241,1673,1699]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
All pereiopods slender (
<figureCitation box="[593,735,1673,1699]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs. 3A–3I</figureCitation>
); first pereiopod small (
<figureCitation box="[1024,1226,1673,1699]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs. 3A, 3B, 3C</figureCitation>
),
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" box="[312,1206,1713,1739]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
First pereiopod about two thirds as long as second pereiopod (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1193,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs. 3D, 3E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,793,1899]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1323,284,390]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Third pereiopod longer than second pereiopod (
<figureCitation box="[887,1041,1753,1779]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Figs. 3F, 3G</figureCitation>
); first pereiopod armed with numerous barbed spines at carpopropodal articulation(
<figureCitation box="[979,1069,1793,1819]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). First.pereiopod and second pereiopod armed with curved tooth on lateral margin of ischium. Chelae with dactylus slightly longer than palm, both dactylus and palm bearing terminal tufts of long setae (
<figureCitation box="[340,545,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Figs. 3C, 3E, 3G</figureCitation>
), fourth pereiopod and fifth pereiopod laterally flattened, bearing natatory setae on all but leading margin of distal two segments (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1243,324,350]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Figs. 3H, 3I</figureCitation>
), fifth pereiopod shorter than of fourth (
<figureCitation box="[654,798,364,390]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[396,1150,284,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-60@5.[396,1152,269,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Sergestes brevispinatus Judkins, 1978. Adult male: A—left first pereiopod; B—carpo­propodal articulation,further enlarged; C—chela of first pereiopod; D—left second pereiopod; E—chela of second pereiopod,further enlarged; F—left third pereiopod; G—chela of third pereiopod further enlarged; H—left fourth pereiopod; I—left fifth pereiopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051224/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Figs. 3H, 3I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051218" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5051218" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" startId="3.[264,367,1826,1850]" targetBox="[368,1234,433,1799]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1322,1826,1884]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
